figgy.title: DRAFT: Implement Embargo Support for ETDs

comments.body: "Walk-in" access is confirmed as being the following currently: if, **after the embargo date has elapsed** a thesis/dissertation has walk-in access set to "yes," this means that users can only access the file at a dedicated desktop machine with a fixed IP, in the Mudd Reading Room.
Additional resource on embargo types - https://undergraduateresearch.princeton.edu/independent-work/thesis-archive

Thanks, @kelynch ! ok. Reading through the embargo types and expectations on that page,  I see a few things in the document you shared that seem contradictory to above (and I just want to make sure I understand correctly). 

- _To enhance the reach and utility of this resource, the [library created a digital archive in 2014 (http://undergraduateresearch.princeton.edu/feature-article/senior-thesis-archive-goes-digital)to enable members of the Princeton University community (our students, faculty, staff) and other authorized users of our computing network to access copies of senior theses online.) :_ This does not sound like Open. This sounds like Princeton University Net ID or getting access to view something via SC?
- Online Access: _accessible online to authorized users of the Princeton University computing network (as described above)._ again, this sounds like Princeton Net ID/access via SC.
- Walk-in Access Only: as you note above. If they want their desktop to hang with Figgy, we had to have Steph A. and her team come in to help with that as well for Special Collections. Has Steph been over there to see what the setup is like? 
Am I reading this correctly?
